I did it. I did my best and that was enough. Thing is, I was so onboard with this yoga journey since the day it started. I‚Äôve been doing yoga for about 2-3 years and have had a regularly practice for about a year now, but i woke up feeling a bit sick on day 3 and said I would just do this session after work instead of in the morning so I could get some extra rest. That didn‚Äôt happen because I felt sicker at night and by day 4 I was horribly sick. Turns out I had Covid. I was taking good care of myself but I‚Äôm also immunocompromised due to medicine I took for a flare up in my autoimmune disease. I got over the symptoms in about 5 days, but had a sinus infection the week after. And since being sick, I have been dealing with fatigue. However, a friend of mine told me that napping wouldn‚Äôt help fatigue as much, and that, instead, take it easy don‚Äôt overwork and try to get moving gradually. So last week I decided I felt okay enough to restart this journey, even if it takes more than 30 days. Move is perfect because it eases us into yoga and it seems like everyone who finished it felt much stronger when they finished! Although I‚Äôm bummed I couldn‚Äôt practice live with everyone and i‚Äôm rather disheartened because i don‚Äôt feel like I‚Äôm in my own body (seriously‚Ä¶I used to be able to do a lot of this with strength, grace, and a smile on my face, but now? It‚Äôs so hard for meüòì), I‚Äôm glad this journey is available to everyone for free. Adriene, thank you for all you do. I‚Äôm in the middle of a sucky setback, but I will be strong again and I will feel like myself again soon. I‚Äôm doing my best, and that is enough. Namaste‚ù§Ô∏è

"You get to decide how you move in life."
This. This is why I love YWA! In a society that pressures us to move in very specific ways (ways which are often rigid and practiced on a basis of self-punishment), YWA rejects generalization and gives the individual the power to determine what feels good on a given day. We are not static, and our needs change. Movement is not a one-size-fits-all (what is, really?), and that is the beauty of being human.

A few reflections from me: First of all, on a practical note, the hints about when it might be useful to glance at the screen were very helpful! Since all of this is new to me, there's a risk I end up trying to hold poses while cricking my neck to stare at the screen!

Second, that session felt physically easier than day 2 for me, in terms of holding the poses. If anything, that allowed me to focus more on my breathing. At some point - I think about 17:01 in the video - I inhaled and was suddenly very much aware that the inhalation was pushing me sideways with how it made my body move. I felt particularly aware of the way my breath was making my body move, then, in a way that's quite unlike anything I've done before.

Third, in child's pose (I think it was called?) at the end, a light behind me was being reflected in my glasses, and the reflection was changing from red-tinted to green-tinted as I inhaled and exhaled and changed the position of my head and the lenses ever so slightly. A complete coincidence, and I'm not sure I could set it up again if I tried, but that was satisfying to be aware of!

For those of you who are struggling: There‚Äôs some great warm up videos for the wrists and shoulders. It isn‚Äôt uncommon for newbies to get really sore wrists and shoulders. How do I know? because that was me 2 years ago! I still do 2 to 5 minutes of wrist and shoulder warm ups beforehand. Yoga Tx has a great warm up video! I am dealing with a hip injury and have done research to see what to do and what avoid and how to modify. If something hurts, don‚Äôt do it. You can hurt yourself. Instead, remember the name of the pose and research it. You may just need some tips or it may not be right for you. Modify and listen to your body and breathe, that‚Äôs how you will get the most out of your practice. You can do it!
